[4] Indonesia, East Java, Madura Island
Date: Thu 15 Feb 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Antara News [edited]
<http://www.antara.co.id/en/seenws/?id=27517>

Some poultry culled in Bangkalan, Madura
-----------------------------------------------
Some 50 poultry were culled in Bangkalan, Madura Island, East Java
Province, following a finding of bird flu (Avian Influenza/AI) virus
infection in the area recently. [See map at
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ID/8/Bangkalan.html>.
- Mod.AS]
"The poultry culling is aimed at stopping the bird flu virus from
spreading to wider areas," Head of the Bangkalan Health Service Dr.
Fahrurrozi said here [Bangkalan, Madura Island, East Java Province]
on Thu 15 Feb 2007.
Bangkalan District Head Fuad Amin Imron has called for efforts to
control bird flu virus by culling poultry within a radius of 100
meters from the location where the bird flu infection was detected
earlier.
There is no human infected with bird flu virus in Bangkalan so far,
but the district has intensified surveillance by spraying
disinfectant in poultry breeding areas and launching a public
awareness campaign on the deadly disease.
The local administration has provided compensation worth Rp 40 000
[USD 4.42] for each animal being culled.
A total of 10 nations have detected outbreaks of the animal disease
in humans. Indonesia has verified more human cases of H5N1 infection
than any other country in 2006. Of around 80 cases confirmed in
Indonesia, 62 have been fatal.
Like the vast majority of other human cases detected throughout the
region, contact with ailing chickens around households is the
apparent means by which the latest human cases occurred.
An Indonesian official announced recently that the Indonesian
government would allocate USD 61 million for an anti-bird flu drive
next year [2008], an increase from the USD 55 million it budgeted
this year.
President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono has instructed all regional
authorities to promptly provide compensation funds to people and
farmers whose poultry have to be culled to fight bird flu.
The President said Indonesia had come into the world's spotlight
because it was supposed to be able to do more to fight the bird flu
virus.
--
